H. Checking the correlation between nutritional contents with each other and with nutri-score

In [14]:
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 3))
sns.heatmap(OFF_data.select_dtypes(include='float64').corr(method='pearson'),
            vmin=-1, vmax=1, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt="0.2f")
plt.xticks(ha='right', rotation=45, rotation_mode='anchor')
plt.show()

Observations:

  • Nutrional contents correlation with each others:

    • There is high positive correlation between fat and energy which is logic. Fat is the most dense product on energy with 9Kcal/g.
    • There is high positive correlation as well between saturated_fat and fat which is logic because saturated_fat belong to fat macronutrients. This tell us as well that the products saturated_fat contents highly follows the fat contents.
    • There is high correlation as well between sugars and carbohydrates which is logic because they belong to the same group. This tell us as well that the products sugars contents highly follows the carbohydrates contents. We see as well that fiber follow carbohydrate by to a lesser degree than sugars.

  • Nutrional contents correlation to nutri-score:

    • There is positive correlation of energy, fat, saturated_fat, sugars, and to a lesser degree carbohydrates with the nutri-score which is logic. Products with good nutritional value (low nutri-score) are low on energy, fat, saturated_fat, and sugars.
    • There is slight negative correlation of fiber with the nutri-score which is logic as well. Products high on fiber provide good nutritional value.
    • There is no or very small positive correlation of protein and sodium with nutri-score.

I. Analysis of Variance (ANOVA)

In [15]:
# Measuring of effect size, eta squared between two variables, one qualitative and one quantitative.
def eta_squared(x, y):
    moyenne_y = y.mean()
    classes = []
    for classe in x.unique():
        yi_classe = y[x == classe]
        classes.append({'ni': len(yi_classe),
                        'moyenne_classe': yi_classe.mean()})
    SCT = sum([(yj-moyenne_y)**2 for yj in y])
    SCE = sum([c['ni']*(c['moyenne_classe']-moyenne_y)**2 for c in classes])
    return round(SCE/SCT, 2)

# Plotting the distributions of quantitative columns for each pnns_group_1 category
columns_list = OFF_data.select_dtypes(include='float64').columns
n_sub = len(columns_list)
n_col = 3
fig, axes = plt.subplots(int(round((0.49+n_sub/n_col), 0)), n_col, figsize=(20, int(2*n_sub)))
axes = np.array(axes)
i = 0
for ax in axes.reshape(-1):   
    groupes = []
    for m in OFF_data['pnns_groups_1'].unique():
        groupes.append(OFF_data[OFF_data['pnns_groups_1'] == m][columns_list[i]])
    eta_squared_value = eta_squared(OFF_data['pnns_groups_1'], OFF_data[columns_list[i]])
    ax.boxplot(groupes, labels=OFF_data['pnns_groups_1'].unique(),
               showfliers=False, vert=False, patch_artist=True, showmeans=True)
    ax.set_title('Distribution of {} (effect size eta^2: {})'.format(columns_list[i], eta_squared_value))
    ax.set_xlabel(format(columns_list[i]))
    i+=1
plt.show()

Observations:

  • For the nutriscore distribution, as discussed before, fruit and vegetables, and cereals and potatoes have better nutri-score than other categories. Sugary snacks have bad nutri-score.
  • For the energy distribution, Beverages have low energy which is logic due to their liquid state. We see that Salty snacks and sugary snacks have high energy because they are dense on sugar and fat.
  • For the fat distribution, beverages, fruits and vegetables are low on fat which is logic. We seee that salty snacks high on fat which validate the previous point of salty snacks being high on energy as well. This is followed by fat and sauces as being high on fat.
  • For the saturated-fat ditribution, beverages, fuits and vegetables are again low on saturated-fat. Milk and dairy products are high on saturated fat which is known phenomena.
  • For the carbohydrates distribution, Fish meats and eggs are low on carbohydrates which is logic because these products are known to be sources of protein and fat. Sugary snacks, cereals and potatoes are high on carbohydrate which is again logic because sugary snacks are known to be high on sugars and cerals and potatoes to be a sources of carbohydrates.
  • For the sugars distribution, we see sugary snacks to be the top of the podium since these products are known to be high on sugars.
  • For the fiber distribution, we see fruits and vegetables, cereals and potatoes, and salty snacks to be high on fibers.
  • For the proteins distribution, we see fish meats eggs, and milk and dairy products being high on protein which is logic.
  • For the sodium distribution, we see that fat and sauces, salty snacks, fish meat eggs to be higher on sodium than other.

From the value of effect size eta_squared, we see that there is big effect of the category of the products and the carbohydrates and sugars (highest eta_squared value). We see that sodium has the lowest effect from the category of the products (near zero eta_squared).

Now we can do the same but this time using the top 10 pnns_group_2 sub-category of the product.

# Plotting the distributions of quantitative columns for each pnns_group_2 sub-category
columns_list = OFF_data.select_dtypes(include='float64').columns
n_sub = len(columns_list)
n_col = 3
fig, axes = plt.subplots(int(round((0.49+n_sub/n_col), 0)), n_col, figsize=(20, int(2*n_sub)))
axes = np.array(axes)
i = 0
top_pnns_group_list = OFF_data[(OFF_data['pnns_groups_2'] != 'unknown')].groupby(by='pnns_groups_2').nunique().sort_values('code', ascending=False).head(10).index
for ax in axes.reshape(-1):   
    groupes = []
    for m in top_pnns_group_list:
        groupes.append(OFF_data[OFF_data['pnns_groups_2'] == m][columns_list[i]])
    eta_squared_value = eta_squared(OFF_data['pnns_groups_2'], OFF_data[columns_list[i]])
    ax.boxplot(groupes, labels=top_pnns_group_list, showfliers=False,
               vert=False, patch_artist=True, showmeans=True)
    ax.set_title('Distribution of {} (effect size eta^2: {})'.format(columns_list[i], eta_squared_value))
    ax.set_xlabel(format(columns_list[i]))
    i += 1
plt.show()

Observations:

  • Similar to pnns_group_1, sodium has the lowest effect from the sub_category of the products (near zero eta_squared).
  • Energy, fat, carbohydrate, and fats have the highest effect from the sub_category of the products (highest eta_squared).
  • We see that sweets, biscuit and cakes are the highest on carbohydrates and sugars and have high nutri-score (low nutritional value).
  • We see that cereals and breads are high on carbohydrates and fiber and have the lowest nutriscore (good nutritional value).
  • We see that cheese and processed meat are high on fat, saturated fat and protein and have high nutri-score (bad nutritional value).

Now we can do statistical test to check the correlation between nutri-score and pnns_group_2.

Test the null hypothesis (H0) that all products means are equal vs. the alternative hypothesis (Ha) that at least one mean is different.
In [17]:
# Statistical test
fit = statsmodels.formula.api.ols('nutriscore_score ~ pnns_groups_2', data=OFF_data).fit()
table = statsmodels.api.stats.anova_lm(fit)
print(table)

                      df        sum_sq       mean_sq             F  PR(>F)
pnns_groups_2       39.0  5.364700e+07  1.375564e+06  35250.499017     0.0
Residual       1486607.0  5.801119e+07  3.902255e+01           NaN     NaN

F-stat=35695.34, p_value=0.0 -- reject H0. There is correlation between nutriscore and pnns_group_2.

Observations:

  • For the nutri-score, we see gain the high correlation with nutri-garde which is manifested by the distribution and the value of eta-squared of almost 1.
  • For the energy distribution, we see small correlation with nutri-garde. This is also meaured by the effect size which is not high but not negligeable. We see that a and b grade have lower energy than d and e grade.
  • For the fat and saturated-fat distribution, we can conclude, similar to energy, small correlation to nutri-grade with not high effect size and a and b grade have lower fat and saturated_fat than d and e grade which is logic.
  • For the carbohydrate and fiber distribution, we see very low correlation with nutri-grade which is also shown by the effect size eta_sauqred value of near zero.
  • For the sugars, we see small correlation with nutri-garde and not high eta_squared value. Again a and b grade have lower sugars contents than d and e grade.
  • Finally for the proteins and sodium, we can conclude similar to carbohydrate and fiber that they have very low to no correlation to nutri-grade with eta_squared value near-zero.

Now we can do statistical test to check some of these correlation.

Test the null hypothesis (H0) that all products means are equal vs. the alternative hypothesis (Ha) that at least one mean is different.

def scree_plot_explained_variance_ratio(pca_n_components):  # Plotting explained variance ratio in scree plot
    exp_var_rat = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
    x_list = range(1, pca_n_components+1)
    x_list_name = [f"F{i}" for i in x_list]
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.bar(x_list_name, exp_var_rat)
    ax1 = plt.gca()
    ax1.set(ylim=(0,exp_var_rat.max()*1.1))
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    ax2.plot(x_list_name, exp_var_rat.cumsum(), c='red', marker='o')
    ax2.set(ylim=(0, 1.1))
    ax1.set_ylabel('Explained Variance Ratio')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance Ratio')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Principal Components')

    for i, p in enumerate(ax1.patches):
        ax1.text( p.get_width()/5 + p.get_x(), p.get_height()+ p.get_y()+0.01,
                 '{:.0f}%'.format(exp_var_rat[i]*100),
                 fontsize=8, color='k')
    
    plt.gcf().set_size_inches(8, 3)
    plt.title('Scree plot', fontweight='bold')
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.show()

def heatmap_PCA(df, pca_n_components):  # Showing the PCA components values for each column in a heatmap (or table)
    x_list = range(1, pca_n_components+1)
    list(x_list)
    pca_components_per_columns = pd.DataFrame(pca.components_)
    pca_components_per_columns.columns = df.columns
    pca_components_per_columns.index = [f"F{i}" for i in x_list]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 3))
    sns.heatmap(pca_components_per_columns.round(2).T, vmin=-1,
                vmax=1, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='0.2f')
    ax.set_xlabel('Principal Components')

# Function copied from openclassrooms https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1TKe1_1ECzOlP4Aj1P3vzbn47U9YrqVFQ#scrollTo=HLYtZl7z_kk5
def correlation_graph(pca, x_y, features) : 
    """Affiche le graphe des correlations

    Positional arguments : 
    -----------------------------------
    pca : sklearn.decomposition.PCA : notre objet PCA qui a été fit
    x_y : list ou tuple : le couple x,y des plans à afficher, exemple [0,1] pour F1, F2
    features : list ou tuple : la liste des features (ie des dimensions) à représenter
    """

    # Extrait x et y 
    x,y = x_y

    # Taille de l'image (en inches)
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 6))

    # Pour chaque composante : 
    for i in range(0, pca.components_.shape[1]):

        # Les flèches
        ax.arrow(0, 0,
                 pca.components_[x, i],
                 pca.components_[y, i],
                 head_width=0.07,
                 head_length=0.07,
                 width=0.02)

        # Les labels
        plt.text(pca.components_[x, i] + 0.05,
                 pca.components_[y, i] + 0.05,
                 features[i])
        
    # Affichage des lignes horizontales et verticales
    plt.plot([-1, 1], [0, 0], color='grey', ls='--')
    plt.plot([0, 0], [-1, 1], color='grey', ls='--')

    # Nom des axes, avec le pourcentage d'inertie expliqué
    plt.xlabel('F{} ({}%)'.format(x+1, round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[x],1)))
    plt.ylabel('F{} ({}%)'.format(y+1, round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[y],1)))
    plt.title("Cercle des corrélations (F{} et F{})".format(x+1, y+1))

    # Le cercle
    an = np.linspace(0, 2*np.pi, 100)
    plt.plot(np.cos(an), np.sin(an))  # Add a unit circle for scale

    # Axes et display
    plt.axis('equal')
    plt.show(block=False)

# Function copied from openclassrooms https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1TKe1_1ECzOlP4Aj1P3vzbn47U9YrqVFQ#scrollTo=HLYtZl7z_kk5
def display_factorial_planes(X_projected,
                             x_y,
                             pca=None,
                             labels=None,
                             clusters=None,
                             alpha=1,
                             figsize=[10, 8],
                             marker='.'):
    """
    Affiche la projection des individus

    Positional arguments : 
    -------------------------------------
    X_projected : np.array, pd.DataFrame, list of list : la matrice des points projetés
    x_y : list ou tuple : le couple x,y des plans à afficher, exemple [0,1] pour F1, F2

    Optional arguments : 
    -------------------------------------
    pca : sklearn.decomposition.PCA : un objet PCA qui a été fit, cela nous permettra d'afficher la variance de chaque composante, default = None
    labels : list ou tuple : les labels des individus à projeter, default = None
    clusters : list ou tuple : la liste des clusters auquel appartient chaque individu, default = None
    alpha : float in [0,1] : paramètre de transparence, 0=100% transparent, 1=0% transparent, default = 1
    figsize : list ou tuple : couple width, height qui définit la taille de la figure en inches, default = [10,8] 
    marker : str : le type de marker utilisé pour représenter les individus, points croix etc etc, default = "."
    """

    # Transforme X_projected en np.array
    X_ = np.array(X_projected)

    # On définit la forme de la figure si elle n'a pas été donnée
    if not figsize:
        figsize = (7, 6)

    # On gère les labels
    if  labels is None :
        labels = []
    try :
        len(labels)
    except Exception as e : 
        raise e

    # On vérifie la variable axis 
    if not len(x_y) == 2 : 
        raise AttributeError('2 axes sont demandées')   
    if max(x_y ) >= X_.shape[1] : 
        raise AttributeError('la variable axis n'est pas bonne')   

    # on définit x et y 
    x, y = x_y

    # Initialisation de la figure       
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=figsize)

    # On vérifie s'il y a des clusters ou non
    c = None if clusters is None else clusters
 
    # Les points    
    # plt.scatter(X_[:, x], X_[:, y], alpha=alpha, 
    #             c=c, cmap="Set1", marker=marker)
    sns.scatterplot(data=None, x=X_[:, x], y=X_[:, y], hue=c,
                    hue_order=clusters.sort_values().unique())

    # Si la variable pca a été fournie, on peut calculer le % de variance de chaque axe 
    if pca :
        v1 = str(round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[x]))  + " %"
        v2 = str(round(100*pca.explained_variance_ratio_[y]))  + " %"
    else :
        v1 = v2 = ''

    # Nom des axes, avec le pourcentage d'inertie expliqué
    ax.set_xlabel(f'F{x+1} {v1}')
    ax.set_ylabel(f'F{y+1} {v2}')

    # Valeur x max et y max
    x_max = np.abs(X_[:, x]).max()*1.1
    y_max = np.abs(X_[:, y]).max()*1.1

    # On borne x et y 
    ax.set_xlim(left=-x_max, right=x_max)
    ax.set_ylim(bottom= -y_max, top=y_max)

    # Affichage des lignes horizontales et verticales
    plt.plot([-x_max, x_max], [0, 0], color='grey', alpha=0.8)
    plt.plot([0, 0], [-y_max, y_max], color='grey', alpha=0.8)

    # Affichage des labels des points
    if len(labels) :
        for i, (_x, _y) in enumerate(X_[:, [x, y]]):
            plt.text(_x, _y+0.05, labels[i], fontsize='14',
                     ha='center', va='center') 

    # Titre et display
    plt.title(f"Projection des individus (sur F{x+1} et F{y+1})")
    plt.show()

4. Application

The idea is based on product recommendation based on nutris-core and nutri-grade.

  • I- User input: the user will input the product name or scan the barcode of the product.
  • II- Application search of the product: the application will search the product in the database and the nutritional information related to the product.
    • If the product is not in the database, the application will output to the user that the product in not found in the database.
    • If the product is in the database, the application will proceed to the next step.
      • III- Application check of the product:
        • If the nutri-grade of the product is a, the application will not recommand another product for the user, the application will just display the nutri-grade of the product to the user.
        • If the nutri-grade of the product is not a, the application will search for similar products in the database based on pnns_group_2. The application will proceed to the next step.
          • IV- Application selection of better nutri-grade products: From that pool of similar products, the application will select only those with better nutri-grade.
            • V- Application selection of the best nutri-score product: From those products with better nutri-grade, the application will display to the user the product with the best nutri-score.

Feasibility of the application:

  • The analysis did show the correlation between the different selected columns. The analysis results are found logic with what is known about nutrition and that helped to trust the database.
  • All columns is our database are filled especially the product_name and the barcode. The second step of the application should be fine.
  • Three other variables are used by the application: the nutri-grade, the pnns_group_2, and the nutri-score. We will give the arguments into why these variables can be trusted and used for the purpose of the application.
  • Nutri-grade arguments:
    • The nutri-grade are totally generated for all products with the help of Random Forest Classifier with an error of near 0. This is centainly affect by the nutri-score with was also generated by Random Forest Classifier with an error of around 10%. Since nutri-score was one of the variables used to retrive nutri-grade and due to the high correlation between the two variables, we can say that we have an error of up to 13 % on the generated nutri-grade. At this stage of the application, this error is acceptable and can be used for the checking stage of the product.
    • The logic relation between nutri-garde and nutri-score shown in the analysis (ex. eta_squared value of near 1), the logic relation with the nutritional contents as well as with the pnns_group_1 and with the pnns_group_2 make us trust the nutri-grade parameter.
  • Nutri-score arguments:
    • The nutri-score are totally generated for all products with the help of Random Forest Classifier with an error of around 13%. At this stage of the application, this error is acceptable and can be used for the last step of the application.
    • We see the logic relation between the nutri-score with all nutritional contents as well with pnns_group_1 and top 10 pnns_group_2.
  • pnns_group_2 arguments:
    • pnns_group_2 is also totally generated for all products with the help of Random Forest Classifier with an error of around 4% on the generated sub-category). Surely, pnns_group_1 (error of around 4% on the generated category) was used for that classification. Due to the correlation between pnns_group_1 and pnns_group_2, we can say that pnns_group_2 have up to 8% error on the generated data. At this stage of the application, this error is acceptable and can be used for the searching of similar products based on pnns_group_2.
    • The logic relation of the top 10 pnns_group_2 with the nutritional contents of the product as well as with nutri-grade and nutri-score make us trust the database for the application purpose.

5. Conclusion and Future improvement

Conclusion:

  • From all the column in the initial database, we select only the most important columns. There is other columns that are needed for future improvement of the application and for better selection/recommendation of the products to the user but they are less important at this stage of the application.
  • The analysis helped to drop Nova_group and fruit-vegetable-nuts column from our databse sinc ethey don't make sense. Using ACP, we can reduce dimentionally our 7 nutrional contents variables into 4 dimensions. The pnns_group_1 can also be dropped since pnns_group_2 is provided in the database. This reduce the dimension of our databse to 11 variables.

For future improvement:

  • If the input product is not in the database, the application can ask the user to input the nutritional informations or take an photo of the product as well aa a photo of the product nutritional informations. This information can then be used to input that product to the database and perform the cleaning procedure in the cleaning_notebook.
  • The application can use the IP address of the user to recommend a product sold in that country. For that, the column countries have to be included in the cleaning notebook.
  • Following that, the application can also use the ecoscore_grade to recommend a product with better ecoscore. For that, the column ecoscore have to be included in the cleaning notebook.
